<!-- ═══ 90-DAY WINDOW ═══ -->
<div class="section-label">Section 06 &mdash; The 90-Day Window</div>
<h2 class="section-title">Where the Market Is Still Open</h2>
<p class="section-intro">The dominant positions on primary terms are held by well-resourced operators with years of accumulated authority. That is the honest picture. The opportunity is on the secondary terms — and the clock is running.</p>

<div class="window-grid">
  <div class="window-card dark">
    <div class="window-num">2–4</div>
    <div class="window-title">Years of authority held by top 3 operators</div>
    <div class="window-body">Parker &amp; Sons, The Aussie Plumber, and Maloney have built review volume, domain authority, and backlink profiles that require significant time to replicate. Competing for "plumber Phoenix AZ" head-on requires multi-year investment. That is the realistic baseline.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="window-card">
    <div class="window-num">60–90</div>
    <div class="window-title">Days to shift Map Pack on secondary terms</div>
    <div class="window-body">Water heater repair, drain cleaning, emergency plumbing, and sewer repair are still open. Review velocity, GBP optimization, and service-area page development are the primary levers. Consistent execution over one quarter produces measurable movement.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="window-card">
    <div class="window-num">7</div>
    <div class="window-title">High-reputation operators losing revenue daily</div>
    <div class="window-body">Wyman Plumbing (5.0★, 1,517 reviews), Somers Plumbers (5.0★, 295 reviews), and Elite Rooter (4.8★, 1,405 reviews) hold exceptional ratings. They are virtually invisible in search. That is a correctable gap with 90 days of focused effort.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="window-card dark">
    <div class="window-num">Now</div>
    <div class="window-title">The window for secondary terms is open — it will not stay open</div>
    <div class="window-body">Secondary terms are consolidating. Every month without action is a month those positions become harder to take. The operators who move in Q1 2026 will have a structural advantage by Q4. The cost to compete increases with every quarter of delay.</div>
  </div>
</div>

